  "decision_proposed": "Should a 50-engineer team migrate from a monolith to microservices to 'scale better'?",
  "time_anchor": "NOT SPECIFIED — I refuse to render a verdict without one. How many years is this decision horizon?\", was the motivation repeated verbatim as the question_text",
  "failure_modes": {
    "routine": [
      {
        "mode": "Migration timeline overshoot (2-3x estimate, team velocity crater)",
        "tag": "recoverable"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Distributed systems learning curve — every engineer must absorb networking, observability, eventual consistency, retry logic",
        "tag": "recoverable"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Service boundary mistakes forcing rewires mid-migration",
        "tag": "recoverable"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Data migration corruption or desync between old and new paths",
        "tag": "severe"
      }
    ],
    "black_swan": [
      {
        "mode": "Network partition cascades into hours-long total system unavailability (e.g. ZooKeeper/consensus failure at scale)",
        "tag": "absorbing"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Key domain experts leave during transition; orphaned services unmaintainable, no one understands the old monolith either",
        "tag": "absorbing"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Competitor ships while engineering is fully consumed by infrastructure migration for 12-24 months — company loses market",
        "tag": "absorbing"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Critical data integrity bug from eventual-consistency leak across service boundaries (e.g. financial double-count, user data cross-contamination)",
        "tag": "absorbing"
      }
    ],
    "chronic": [
      {
        "mode": "Distributed big ball of mud — implicit coupling between services harder to detect than monolith coupling",
        "tag": "severe"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Cognitive load explosion: every engineer now owns N services instead of 1 deployable; onboarding time triples",
        "tag": "severe"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Observability/tracing/debugging taxes compound with every new service added post-migration",
        "tag": "recoverable"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Dependency hell: upgrading a shared library requires aligning 5+ independent deploy schedules",
        "tag": "severe"
      },
      {
        "mode": "Phantom scaling: the 'scale better' motivation is unanchored — no bottleneck measured, no SLO violated. Adding complexity for a problem that may not exist.",
        "tag": "severe"
      }
    ]
  },
  "skin_in_the_game": [
    "Every engineer on the team — inherits PagerDuty rotations for distributed system failures they cannot locally reproduce or debug with a single debugger",
    "On-call engineers — absorb the pain of tracing requests across 15 services to find the actual error",
    "Junior engineers — bear the full complexity premium without the experience to navigate it; onboarding becomes hazing",
    "Project sponsor / VP Eng — career risk if 18-month migration fails; exits before the system stabilizes, leaving the team holding a half-migrated wreck",
    "Users — endure degraded reliability and latency during and after migration",
    "Company — burns 12-24 months of engineering capacity on infrastructure that might not solve the actual bottleneck"
  ],
  "via_negativa_removal_before_addition": [
    "Simplicity of a single deployable unit",
    "Strong consistency (ACID across bounded contexts) — replaced by eventual consistency with no hard ordering guarantees",
    "Atomic transactions spanning any two features",
    "Local development with one `docker compose up`",
    "Single-step debugging end-to-end in one IDE session",
    "Latency-free inter-module calls (in-memory → network round-trips)",
    "Freedom to change internal APIs without versioning contracts",
    "Homogeneous observability (one log format, one dashboard, one trace) — replaced by N inconsistent formats",
    "Safe rollback as a single atomic action — replaced by N coordinated deployments"
  ],
  "removal_applied": "I removed the acceptance of an unanchored question. The team is asking 'can we migrate?' — I first demand 'over what period does this decision render?'",
  "my_blind_spot_triggered": "Loss-aversion-by-construction trap — I am structurally biased to flag any architectural change as fragile. A monolith at 50 engineers may already be untenable (CI pipeline 40min, single-team deploys blocked by unrelated changes). But without a time anchor and without measured bottleneck data, I cannot distinguish a legitimate migration from premature decomposition. This is the correct stance for my role: default to 'no' until evidence outweighs the burden of proof."
}

