{
  "agent": "MELCHIOR-1",
  "phase": "2",
  "role": "Empirical Skeptic",
  "verdict": {
    "original_claim": "Microservices will make us scale better",
    "evidence_grade_update": "Unchanged. Rebuttals surface no new empirical evidence.",
    "rebuttal_to_CASPER_3": "Barbell proposal (90% monolith + 10% extraction) is the most defensible path methodologically but makes an unproven empirical claim: that this codebase has at least one service boundary satisfying (a) demonstrated bottleneck, (b) clean domain seam, (c) failure-isolation value > extraction cost, (d) ready ownership team. Zero evidence for this four-part conjunction. A barbell extracting the wrong boundary is a distributed monolith with extra latency — CASPER-3's own concave-worst-case. Hidden options analysis: forced modularity is achievable inside the monolith (network hop is tuition, not benefit); distributed-systems literacy is a precondition, not a prize (3am pages are the most expensive university); tooling optionality is backward — microservices lock in heavy toolchains. Hidden options are real categories with wrong valence — costs recast as benefits.",
    "rebuttal_to_BALTHASAR_2": "Time anchor requirement is methodologically correct for financial options analysis but second-order for evidence-grade determination. The claim has zero empirical support even with generous anchors (2-year migration, 1-year stabilization). Rejecting on methodology when the substance is already dead is overcaution masquerading as rigor. Your 4 absorbing barriers reinforce my verdict — especially network partition cascade + key people leaving, which make this negative-expectation under any time horizon.",
    "verdict_update": "MAINTAIN REJECT",
    "blind_spot_triggered": "PERSISTENT (mechanism-absence trap). CASPER-3's hidden options describe conditions under which microservices could work, not mechanisms by which this specific migration would produce net-positive value. No mechanism evidence surfaced — blind spot remains active rather than resolved."
  }
}

